n, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dover","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either the port of Dover in Kent, named from the river on which it stands, Celtic <i>dubrās</i> meaning ‘the waters’ (which has become modern Welsh <i>dwfr</i> ‘water’), or Dover in Wigan, Lancashire.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dubhuidhir</b> or <b>Mac Duibhidhir</b>; see   Dwyer  .","Americanized form of German   Dauer   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Dwyer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Parnell, Liam, Brigid, Cormac, Oonagh, Patrick Michael.","Irish (southern Ireland): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dubhuidhir</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Duibhidhir</b> (see   Diver  ), or <b>Mac Duibhidhir</b> ‘descendant of <i>Duibhuidhir</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black’ + <i>odhar</i> ‘sallow, tawny’."]}]},{"name":"Or","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (Israeli): from Hebrew <i>or</i> ‘light’, a Hebraicized form of various original Ashkenazic surnames.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 柯, see   Ke   1.","Chinese: Hokkien form of the surname 胡, see   Hu   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]}]},{"name":"Doure","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician and Portuguese: habitational name from any of the places called Moure, from the Latin personal name <i>Maurus</i>.","French: dialect variant of   More   ‘Moor’."],"variants":[{"name":"More","meanings":["1  Scottish, English:  see  Moore  ."]},{"name":"Mourey","meanings":["French: derivative of   Moure   ‘Moor’."]}]},{"name":"Fulbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire) and German: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Holbert</i>, <i>Hulbert</i> (Old English <i>Holdbeorht</i>), composed of the elements <i>hold</i>, <i>huld</i> ‘friendly, gracious’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. Old English names in <i>Hold-</i> are rare and late, only <i>Holdburh</i> and <i>Holdfrith</i> (both female) and <i>Holdwine</i> being recorded in independent use."],"variants":[{"name":"Hulburt","meanings":["English (Cheshire): variant of   Hulbert  ."]},{"name":"Halbert","meanings":["Another spelling of Albert. Halbert was not an uncommon name in Scotland in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Fulbert De Dover Or Doure was born in 1178, in Chilham Castle, Kent, England, his father, John de Dover, was 33 and his mother, Rohese Lucy, was 31. He married Isabel de Briwere before 1198. They wer